💗 LADY FOR SALE is ONE YEAR OLD AND ALL GROWN UP! 💗

I’m taking some time today to reflect on all the fun, friends and fucking awesomeness she has brought into my life!!! Here are some of my favorite #ladyforsale memories!!! Tell me about yours in the comment section!!!

OR just read this very long post! Either way! Here I go!

If you had told me when I first started out that I’d get to tour with legends like @elleking, @courtneymarieandrews, @firstaidkitband, and @missmargoprice I WOULDN’T HAVE BELIEVED YOU! That icons like @jennydianelewis + @alexishotchip would have wanted to open for me (wtf?!) I would have asked what you were smoking!!! That I could have sold out shows of my own in cities I love like London, Nashville and Los Angeles I would have gasped. That I would have gotten to make a workout video (seriously tho have you watched it yet?!) AND a Christmas special—even though I’m Jewish—and have the wonderful amazing @officialjackwhite’s @thirdmanrecords say “ok yes that sounds good”… well shit. 

I feel so lucky and grateful to all my many collaborators and supporters. 
Thank you a million to everyone who has showed up and sang along and made this journey (YES I SAID “journey” so what?!) so special. 

I am so grateful. Thank you. Wow.

Western AF Presents Lola Kirke “All My Exes Live in L.A.” ( Field Recording )
...
The California desert seemed to be a perfect location for a video featuring break up song. We couldn’t have imagined a better performer than country singer-songwriter Lola Kirke. She dazzled us at Stagecoach 2023 on Nikki Lane’s Horseshoe stage. 

Lola released her first full length record “Heart Head West” through Downtown Records five years ago. Releasing a couple of singles between then and now, her sophomore album “Lady For Sale” on Third Man Records is an amazing combination of country and almost 80’s rock pop. It’s definitely a playful album about falling in love when you shouldn’t fall in love. 

Off the cuff, Lola is not only a great performer, but a hellarious wisecracker. Not mention so open with sharing incredible stories with us. The whole experience was fondly memorable.

Check out the full video at Western AF’s YouTube page

I may have left LA, but I brought my Acqua Panna.

Years ago, I was on tour in Seattle looking for a place to eat late after a gig. Eventually a waitress was kind enough to let me in to her restaurant after closing. As I settled up, she told me she’d been a fan of mine since seeing me on tv once because I made her feel beautiful: my body empowered her to feel good in hers. I thanked her but the truth is, I felt insulted. When I saw actresses on screen, I always felt worse about my body. Not better. Somehow, her words seemed to confirm long held beliefs I had about myself. I’m too fat or I eat too much. That I lack self control because I can’t be like girls who don’t eat dairy or gluten or sugar or any of my other favorite things. 

Often, these thoughts push me to consider my options: Ozempic. Lypo. Fat freezing. Starving myself. Adderall so I won’t feel it. But I know attempting to resolve my deep seated insecurities externally will always elude me. And the truth is, despite all the negative self talk, a lot of the time I actually really like my body. I like its curves and folds. I feel lucky that it works so well. When I am alone with myself, in my nightgown, I feel beautiful. It’s only when I compare it to others that the shame kicks in.

Living in a society that tries to convince us we are only valuable if we look, act, sound or are like everyone else, it can be hard to remember individuality is not weakness. It is strength.
Today, I feel honored that mine helped another person to embrace her own. I hope I can continue to do that and remember that’s even possible whenever I feeling like caving to societal pressure. 

It is a wonderful thing to look like yourself. I’d like to forget that less. To those who relate, I hope this makes you feel as beautiful as you already are. To all, have a beautiful weekend.
